## 9. CONTEXT & CONCURRENCY

```go
// Context propagation — always first argument
func (s *OrderService) Create(ctx context.Context, order *Order) error { ... }

// Goroutines — always handle lifecycle
func (w *Worker) Start(ctx context.Context) error {
    g, ctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
    g.Go(func() error { return w.processLoop(ctx) })
    g.Go(func() error { return w.cleanupLoop(ctx) })
    return g.Wait()
}

// Channel patterns — always buffer if sender shouldn't block
jobs := make(chan Job, 100)

// Mutex — embed in the type it protects
type Cache struct {
    mu    sync.RWMutex
    items map[string]Item
}
```

### Rules

- Context is always the **first parameter**, never stored in structs.
- Never create goroutines without a clear ownership and shutdown story.
- Use `errgroup` (`golang.org/x/sync/errgroup`) for concurrent work with error propagation.
- Use `sync.WaitGroup` only when errors don't need to propagate.
- Mutexes: embed in the struct they protect. Document what they guard with a comment.
- Channels: close on the sender side only. Never close from the receiver.
- `select` with `ctx.Done()`: every blocking goroutine must respect context cancellation.
- Never use `time.Sleep` in hot paths — use timers or tickers with `ctx.Done()` select.

