## 16. DO NOT

- Use `init()` functions — initialization order is invisible and untestable
- Use global variables for anything other than `var ErrFoo = errors.New(...)` sentinel errors
- Use `interface{}` / `any` unless absolutely necessary — use generics (Go 1.18+) instead
- Copy a `sync.Mutex` — always pass by pointer
- Ignore `error` return values, even in `defer` — use a named return or log
- Use `panic` for expected error conditions — only for true programmer errors
- Write God structs or God services — a service with 20 methods needs to be split
- Grow a single `*.go` into a junk drawer of unrelated handlers, stores, and types — split by responsibility before it crosses the file-size bar under **Project structure**
- Hardcode timeouts as integer literals — use `time.Duration` constants
- Use `time.Now()` directly in business logic — inject a clock for testability
- Share `*http.Client` created with default settings — always set timeouts
- Return `200 OK` with an error body — use the correct HTTP status code
- Mix concerns: handlers must not contain SQL, stores must not contain HTTP logic
- Use `log.Fatal` outside of `main.go` — it calls `os.Exit` and skips deferred cleanup
- Use `context.Background()` inside request handlers — propagate the request context
- Write tests that depend on execution order or shared mutable state

